full_text:
LOOK: Josenian alumnus and Rappler Visayas Reporter John Sebastian Sitchon discussed the struggles of the campus press and how to combat censorship in his talk “Campus Journalism: Where are we now?” at the Marcelo B. Fernan Press Center on Saturday, March 23.

Sitchon gave a quick refresher on the Campus Journalism Act of 1991 to reiterate the rights of student journalists as cases of censorship rise in Central Visayas universities.

Further, he is one of the speakers in the first-ever Metro Cebu Collegiate Publication Summit organized by SCIRE Publication, the official student publication of the University of San Carlos Carolinian Political Science Society (USC-CPSS).

via Ava Donalie Ferolino | FORWARD Staff Writer

full_text:
JUST IN: Seven Josenian grads land the top spots in the November 2023 Registered Business Professionals (RBP) Examination, as released by the Junior Achievement of the Philippines Incorporated (JAPI) today, March 22.

These topnotchers are Demi Eloise N. Oroc (Top 2), Niña Jane Olimba (Top 3), Earl Christian C. Rebosura (Top 4), Angel May G. Flores (Top 5), Kirs Nicko R. Busante (Top 7), Christine Joy D. Honofre (Top 8 ), and Cherrymae A. Barangan (Top 9).

Meanwhile, two Josenians also clinched the eighth and ninth spots in the Registered Marketing Professionals (RMP) Examination, namely Lovely Queen P. Gatdula (Top 8 ) and Daphnie Rose D. Mananquil (Top 9).

LOOK: The University of San Jose-Recoletos Department of Psychology and Library and Information Science (USJ-R DPLIS) organized a research seminar titled, “Pep Talk: The Anatomy of Research” at the Recoletos Center for Arts and Culture (RCAC) on Friday, March 22.

The symposium was intended for second-year Psychology students taking the Field Methods in Psychology course in preparation for their Thesis Writing in the next Academic Year.

Research professors Ethel Luz Medado, Ian Jarabelo, and Janson Toledo discussed about the research introduction, methodologies, and oral defense, respectively.

Further, School of Arts and Sciences (SAS) Dean Dr. Marietta Bongcales and DPLIS Chair Maryjun Delgado were also in attendance at the seminar.

via Rufino Rico Jamisola | FORWARD Staff Writer

full_text:
[LITERARY]

Timeless Stranger
by Egret

I stare aimlessly at the ceiling, curled upright on the headboard, unconcerned with time’s passage, as it holds no relevance for me. The ghost of the past haunts me in the room’s corner, dimly lit by moonshine from the satellite-carve
d crescent by the smoke from distant missiles.

You sit there in peace, but I cannot.

Not with you here.

The details seem to shift. The surface of the room morphs before my eyes.

Am I dreaming? I don’t know. I was never sure.

From pale yellow walls, they turn grainy—resembli
ng the noise on a television screen, reminiscent of the bustling city park, resonating with the echoes of the perverted and deadly warheads.

“What has this world gone into?” I say to myself as I watch complicit with men.

I do not talk, for you cannot hear me.

You, too, appear to be changing.

Your eyes gleam with wonder—like when you were five and you were thrown in the air by your father. Your hair brushes through the midnight breeze—like when you ran from your home at twelve. Your collar’s still stained with the coffee you spilled while rushing through the university halls.

You reek of cruelty as the air carries your inhumanity to me.

Curious as I am, you are familiar, yet I do not wish to know you further.

What have you gone through? What have you become? How long has it been since you waited for me?

The unknown looms before you, yet you persist in visiting my room. I do not wish for this to be mutual. Not any longer.

I have granted you ample time, yet you have bestowed upon me sorrow.

You are the past; I am merely to be what is. I am soon to be; you were once.

Why do you come to me only when you need to and not when you want? I, too, am something to be cared for.

Speak to me. You only dare sit up close, but remain ensconced in silence. Is it because you know what you did? Or is it that you refuse to?

You anger me as much as you hurt and wound me.

Do I scare you? Why did you come to me?

I remember you—innocent. You still are. Yet you rush towards things you are still not capable of.

I cared for you in silence, even though you were careless to begin with. You were always spilling your drink on the pavement as you rushed towards me. Now, the only stain you’ve spilled is blood—etched vainly on my raggedy rug.

You’ve spiraled out for your own sanity’s sake.

With cusped lips from years of silence, I finally utter a greeting.

“Hello.”

You stand up. Like the elder that you are, your legs shake in agony.

“Mom?”

“Dad?”

You cling to hope, as you always do.

“I miss you.”

Crazed and corrupted.

Innocent and stupid.

I do not answer, for you will not hear me. Yet I whisper in pity, “What have you become?”

We exist as mere parallels—almos
t converging, yet never quite meeting halfway.

You keep coming back, reverting to habits of old.

I begin to hear sobs.

Are they yours? I do not know, for I cannot see. You won’t let me.

You hide your grievance in pride, and I sit here and let you be. I could do nothing, yet I know everything. Because you keep coming back to me.

Night after night, you quietly open the door, careful not to wake the peacefully slumbering, ensuring they remain oblivious to the crimes you’ve committed against your own kind. You hang your heavy coat on the coat rack downstairs, longing to leave the weight as you step inside my abode at midnight. Always.

You practice this nightly now. And yet I do nothing but wait—wait for you to leave. You want me to give you something. A name. A solution. A pearl of wisdom. But I just cannot. Not yet.

But alas, you do not know me, still. No matter how, you couldn’t.

I sleep peacefully at times. I caught you looking out the window.

What do you want to see? What is there outside but the uncertainty of what is and is to be? Do the stars tell you of my being? Do they scream at you for all the heresy you’ve done?

I am a resident of the years to come. You are merely a traveling visitor from then.

Traveler, why do you visit me? Is it because you know I will forgive you, day after day?

I sometimes dream of you. We were friends—little in difference, small in gap. We’ve grown wary of each other now.

I keep pitying you. Enveloped in empathy, as I agonize with you.

Come closer, and I’ll caress your head. I yearn for you to rest.

You are cruel, yet undeniably human. For what are you, if not a sinner? What are you, if not brimming with hope?

An enigma. An obscurity. A gift.

After a while, you come to me.

You hold my cold hands in yours. I get a glimpse of your glistening stare. There are no questions at this moment.

There, there.

You have done enough.

Rest now, and go forth at sunrise.

Time and time again, I’ll be here—steadfast and constant.

I’ll always be the day after, as you are the past.

Return to me at sunset as a child. Leave me as a wiser man.

Let this be my present, as you visit me on the morrow, once more.

Illustration by Khen Fernandez | FORWARD Staff Artist[LITERARY]

full_text:
#USJRadvisory | Here are the guidelines of the University for this year's Holy Week.

Classes on March 25 and 26 for college students will be transitioned to asynchronous mode. Meanwhile, online classes will be conducted for the JHS and SHS students. Furthermore, classes in the School of Law, Graduate School, ETEEAP and CPA-Review will be at the discretion of their respective deans and directors.

Faculty members with poor connectivity at home may opt to come to school for their classes. Physical classes will resume on April 1, Monday.

In addition, the annual "Adlaw sa Pagpamalandong"
for USJ-R employees (office professionals, faculty, academic non-teaching faculty) is scheduled on Holy Wednesday, March 27 at the Recoletos Center for Arts & Culture (RCAC) with Rev. Fr. Kenneth Joseph L. Onda, OAR. With this in mind, there are no classes on Wednesday.

Offices are still open for business transactions on March 25 and 26.

May we all be one in our journey with our Lord in His Paschal Mystery. Have a Blessed Holy Week.#USJRadvisory | Here are the guidelines of the University for this year's Holy Week.

for USJ-R employees (office professionals, faculty, academic non-teaching faculty) is scheduled on Holy Wednesday, March 27 at the Recoletos Center for Arts & Culture (RCAC) with Rev. Fr. Kenneth Joseph L. Onda, OAR. With this in mind, there are no classes on Wednesday.

Offices are still open for business transactions on March 25 and 26.
